          <div class="article-intro">
            <p class="lead">Vaughan regulates short-term rentals under <strong>By-Law 158-2019</strong>, which has been amended several times through 2025. If you're thinking about listing your property on Airbnb or VRBO in Vaughan, understanding these rules is essential for staying compliant and avoiding significant penalties.</p>
            <p class="lead">This guide covers everything you need to know about Vaughan's STR regulations, from the principal residence requirement to licensing, background checks, and the 4% Municipal Accommodation Tax.</p>
          </div>

          <h2 id="what-is-str">What Counts as a Short-Term Rental?</h2>
          <p>Under Vaughan's bylaw, a short-term rental is defined as:</p>

          <blockquote class="bylaw-quote">
            "Short-Term Rental means a Dwelling Unit or part of a Dwelling Unit used to provide temporary accommodation for a Rental Period of not more than 29 consecutive days and shall not include a hotel, motel or Bed-and-Breakfast Establishment."
            <cite>Vaughan By-Law 158-2019, Section 3.0(4)(cc)</cite>
          </blockquote>

          <p>This means any rental of 29 days or less requires licensing and must follow all STR regulations. Rentals of 30 consecutive days or more are not considered short-term rentals and are exempt from these rules.</p>

          <div class="callout">
            <div class="callout-icon">
